<DOCNO> AP890411-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in a padlocked shed near the old royal 
palace the limousine of the last afghan king waits in the dust 
the black daimlers tires are flat but the silver royal crest 
on the door is untarnished 
the car is an apt symbol for zahir shah the 74yearold exile 
whose return is talked about by afghans across the political 
spectrum as a way of ending the decadeold civil war between an 
authoritarian government and moslem fundamentalists 
sixteen years after he was deposed the exking remains a symbol 
of better days of a time when afghans were not slaughtering each 
other in horrific numbers 
the problem is finding a way for him to return 
the car is ready for him it would be good if he came back 
said a man who knew the whereabouts of zahir shahs daimler 
then looking around even though no one else was within hearing 
distance the slender university graduate added please dont 
write my name 
others are less fearful 
if king zahir shah wants to work for his country he can have 
a positive role in bringing peace said wadir safi dean of law 
and political science at kabul university 
even if he didnt do much for the progress of our country he 
didnt kill anybody said safi who studied at czechoslovakias 
charles university 
about a month ago safis views were published in a new weekly 
newspaper the akbarehafta the article was accompanied by the 
first photograph of the former king that kabul residents can 
remember seeing published in the governmentsupervised media since 
zahir shah was overthrown in 1973 
the issue quickly sold out although its price of 20 cents is 
four or five times that of other newspapers even illiterate people 
scrambled for copies 
all the people like zahir shah a shopkeeper said on 
condition of anonymity in zahir shahs time there was not 
killing of people the father of 10 added 
even president najib a former secret police chief has said 
talks with the exking could be useful in midfebruary najib said 
he had sent emissaries to zahir shahs exile home in italy a 
spokesman for the aging exmonarch promptly denied any contacts 
with najibs sovietstyle regime 
usbacked moslem fundamentalist guerrillas operating from 
headquarters across the border in pakistan are divided about 
reinstating the monarchy 
any future role in afghanistan for zahir shah has been rejected 
by hardliners among the rebels such as rasul sayyaf leader of 
one of the seven parties in the pakistanbased guerrilla alliance 
some moderate leaders such as ahmad gailani who once served as the 
kings religious adviser say they would accept his return as a 
constitutional monarch a sort of living flag to help unite the 
afghan people 
the king himself seems amenable 
in early february as the soviet union was withdrawing its last 
soldiers from afghanistan and ending nine years of combat support 
for the kabul government zahir shah said 
i am prepared to render without any claim or precondition any 
service to my country which would reflect the will of the majority 
of my compatriots 
the sticky question is how to reconcile the polesapart politics 
of najibs peoples democratic party of afghanistan the rebels 
islamic fundamentalism and a monarchy 
the rebels refuse to deal with the party whose communist 
beginnings never took root among the fervently capitalist afghans 
the party whose leadership changes have come only through coup 
assassination or purge says it is willing to share power but 
will never step aside completely 
in four decades on the throne zahir shah himself proved a less 
than dynamic leader 
he was only 19 in 1933 when he became king upon the 
assassination of his father nadir shah for the next 20 years his 
uncles ran the country 
in 1953 his cousin mohammad daoud became prime minister and 
tried to push a feudalistic tribal nation toward the 20th century 
by such means as freeing women of their allenveloping robes 
in 1963 zahir shah finally exerted himself daoud resigned 
waited a decade and overthrew his cousin the king 
five years later in 1978 daoud was assassinated in a coup that 
brought the peoples democratic party of afghanistan to power with 
a succession of leaders 
since then about 1 million afghans have been killed in the war 
another 5 million have fled to neighboring paistan and iran 
leaving afghanistan with a population of 10 million 
throughout the war zahir shahs daimler a car that is somehow 
sleek and bulky at the same time has been unscathed 
periodically it is dusted by a man with only childhood memories 
of the monarchy a man who does not want to give his name and hopes 
the car remains safe until the king returns 
the daimler waits along with five other royal automobiles in a 
simple whitewashed structure behind the national museum abou 300 
yards from the early 20th century darulaman palace which now houses 
the defense ministry 
</TEXT>
