<TEXT>
housing and urban development secretary jack 
kemp says his proposals to get drugs out of district of columbia 
housing projects can be followed in the rest of the nation too 
kemp on monday proposed actions against drugs in the federally 
supported housing projects of the nations capital including more 
police patrols installing security fences and guarded entrances 
and requiring photo identification cards for residents 
he announced the moves as part of the federal governments drug 
crackdown in the district of columbia but said the proposals are 
appropriate and will be suggested to every public housing 
authority in the nation 
im asking today the dc police chief and the public housing 
authority of dc along with public housing authorities around the 
country to engage in those type of operations that can clear out 
and secure public housing projects from drug users and abusers and 
dealers kemp said 
in the nations capital kemp said he would waive hud grievance 
hearing requirements that can delay evictions from public housing 
for months kemp took steps recently to remove those requirements 
in virginia 
kemp outlined his plan at a news conference where national drug 
policy director william j bennett and attorney general dick 
thornburgh announced a major new effort to combat drugs in the 
nations capital 
kemp said local police and public housing authorities should 
issue photo identification cards to residents of federally 
supported housing projects so that legitimate residents can be 
distinguished from outsiders 
he said security guards would be trained and a better presence 
of public housing and city police would be provided a part of 
the effort would be a general cleanup of projects including 
removal of graffiti 
kemp acknowledged that many of the steps are things hud should 
be doing anyway and said many of the proposals were based on 
successful tests by local housing authorities at projects in 
chicago omaha and elsewhere 
he said he would finance the antidrug effort with existing 
money appropriated for public housing rehabilitation and operating 
subsidies he put no price tag on the effort 
if its not enough ill ask congress for a supplemental 
appropriation he said 
lucy franklin spokeswoman for washington dcs department of 
public and assisted housing which operates the citys public 
housing projects said city housing officials were discussing 
kemps proposal and had no immediate response 
but she said the district is already issuing photo cards to 
residents of highrise projects for senior citizens most units for 
other residents are apartments or town houses she said and use of 
the cards is a much different issue for families 
she said the district already has asked hud for more money to 
pay for 100 additional housing guards and for more security fences 
kemp said hud also will 
ask us attorneys to seize the apartments of drug dealers and 
return them to the public housing authorities 
seek ways to terminate federal housing subsidies such as hud 
vouchers and housing certificates for anyone convicted of using or 
selling drugs 
attempt to reclaim vacant units sometimes used by drug dealers 
and abusers and enforce housing codes and standards 
encourage resident management of public housing projects 
establish an antidrug hotline to encourage residents to make 
confidential reports on drugrelated crimes 
encourage youth sports leagues in the projects to steer 
youngsters away from drugs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

