<TEXT>
cars could average 33 miles per gallon by 
1995 but automakers are unlikely to make the necessary engineering 
changes on their own the congressional office of technology 
assessment says 
the higher average about 5 mpg above the present one for new 
cars could be reached if automakers began immediately to move 
available fuelconservation technology into their cars at a more 
rapid pace an analyst with the office told a house energy and 
commerce subcommittee on monday 
those changes include better tires more aerodynamic body design 
and engine improvements said steven plotkin senior associate with 
the office 
we calculate that this level of efficiency could be obtained 
without a performance loss or the need to move to smaller vehicles 
at a cost that would be compensated for by fuel savings plotkin 
told the oversight and investigations subcommttee chaired by rep 
john dingell dmich 
but the office doubts that the industry will pursue this 
course without a further economic or regulatory incentive to do 
so plotkin said 
general motors corp and ford motor co have said high 
fueleconomy standards are difficult to reach because of the 
publics demand for larger highpowered cars 
the ota analysis struck a middle course between the positions of 
advocates of tighter fueleconomy standards and the major us 
automakers 
energy conservation groups have proposed a 45 mpg fueleconomy 
goal for cars by 2000 a level plotkin said was virtually 
impossible to reach 
neither gm nor ford could provide estimates of attainable fuel 
efficiency for 1995 
we havent gone out that far in our prognostications largely 
because there are just too many variables to deal with the largest 
of which is fuel cost said gm spokesman gray terry 
the offices analysis assumed a 110 per gallon price for 
gasoline plotkin said 
the corporate average fuel economy standard requires the mix of 
1989 cars sold by each automaker to average 265 mpg or better the 
average fuelefficiency for all new passenger cars in the united 
states in 1987 was 28 mpg and plotkin said the present level is 
about the same 
among the presently available technologies whose adoption could 
improve fuel efficiency are more aerodynamic styling improved tire 
composition and design and improved pumps and other components 
plotkin said 
greater use of frontwheel drive fourspeed automatic shift 
fourcylinder and fourvalve engines and lowfriction rings and 
pistons would also help increase the average fuel efficiency of 
cars in the united states plotkin said 
the goal likely couldnt be reached if present trends toward 
greater performance and luxury continued or if the industry had to 
comply with stricter pollutioncontrol standards that required 
technologies that reduce fuel efficiency plotkin said 
</TEXT>
