<TEXT>
a coalition of environmental groups on 
tuesday sued the state of pennsylvania and the federal government 
alleging they had failed to reduce ozone pollution in the 
philadelphia area 
the lawsuit filed in us district court seeks to block more 
than 100 million in federal highway and cleanair planning grants 
until the state takes action to clean the air 
we believe that pennsylvania has not made a goodfaith effort 
to meet the standards of the clean air act said joseph minott 
executive director of the delaware valley citizens council for 
clean air one of the plaintiffs 
if they wont do it voluntarily well get a court to force 
them to do it he said 
ozone pollution forms when fumes from gasoline and other organic 
chemicals such as cleaning solvents and paint interact with the 
suns heat and light ozone is the principal component of the 
brownish smog that covers philadelphia and other urban areas 
especially in the summer months 
1988 was pennsylvanias worst year for ozone pollution since 
the reauthorization of the clean air act in 1977 said jerome 
balter of the public interest law center lead attorney for the 
council 
a spokesman for the environmental protection agency lee 
blackburn said the federal agency had been expecting the suit but 
he declined to comment on it until he had read the complaint 
susan woods spokeswoman for the state department of 
environmental resources said the state is trying to launch a 
farreaching effort to control ozone pollution with new gasoline 
volatility regulations 
but a state senate committee citing costs and possible gas 
shortages recommended last week that the new rules not go into 
effect completely until 1992 
groups joining in the lawsuit in addition to the delaware 
valley citizens council for clean air include the sierra club 
the delaware valley toxics coalition and the pennsylvania 
federation of sportsmens clubs 
</TEXT>
