<TEXT>
the nassau county police department has 
begun random drug testing in certain narcotics squads making it 
one of the first departments in the nation to test officers for 
drug use 
officers who fail the test will be fired and officers who 
refuse to take it also may be dismissed the program was announced 
to the 200 officers in the drugfighting squads this week and is 
effective immediately 
the policy follows a us supreme court decision which last 
month upheld the right of the us customs service to randomly test 
employees who work on drug interdiction even without reasonable 
suspicion an officer has used drugs 
harry greenberg attorney for the police benevolent association 
in nassau county said the union has not decided whether to 
challenge nassaus new policy 
the program is designed to make the public and officers 
confident of an officers integrity commissioner samuel rozzi said 
he noted that the officers assigned to the drug units including 
undercover agents and police lab workers have ready access to 
drugs 
almost all of our officers are above reproach the finest in 
the country said rozzi whose department on long island numbers 
3200 we want to be able to weed out the one or two who are 
not 
for 15 years the nassau county department has drugscreened 
applicants officers during their first year of probation and 
those under suspicion of drug use since 1983 nine officers and 
two civilian employees have been fired for illegal drug use six of 
the officers were charged with crimes 
in new york city random testing for drugs was started last 
october among the approximately 1000 officers assigned to the 
organized crime control bureau 
boston detroit and chattanooga tenn are awaiting court 
rulings on drug detection programs being fought by their police 
unions 
