maryland lawmakers have ratified a bill 
requiring background checks and a sevenday waiting period for 
buyers of militarystyle semiautomatic assault weapons 
the bill prompted by januarys schoolyard shooting in 
california and by an upswing in street violence involving 
semiautomatic weapons was approved late monday in the closing 
hours of the 1989 general assembly session 
the measure still must be signed by gov william donald 
schaefer whose support is expected 
under the legislation state police would check the background 
of a prospective gun buyer before a sale could be completed the 
sale would be canceled if police found evidence that the applicant 
was a drug addict alcoholic convicted felon or was mentally 
deranged 
purchases of 24 specific gun models are affected and those who 
violate the law would be subject to prison terms of up to three 
years and maximum fines of 10000 
earlier in the 90day session some legislators proposed banning 
the sale of semiautomatics altogether but later modified the 
measure in the face of overwhelming resistance 
in 1988 maryland passed a bill eliminating cheap handguns known 
as saturday night specials the measure established a ninemember 
board to decide which guns may be manufactured and sold in the 
state 
gun control opponents spent 6 million in a losing effort to 
defeat that bill continued pressure from the national rifle 
association has kept lawmakers leery of further weapons legislation 
however lawmakers around the nation have felt pressure to 
control the spread of semiautomatic weapons particularly after 
januarys schoolyard tragedy in stockton calif where a gunman 
killed five children and wounded 30 other people in a rapid burst 
of gunfire from an ak47 
