nearly 25000 children in military families 
nationwide are on waiting lists for child care despite department 
of defense efforts to expand its child care program according to a 
study released tuesday 
the survey conducted by the general accounting office found 
that military child care facilities are providing day care for 
about 62000 children an 82 percent increase over the end of the 
1984 fiscal year 
two types of care are available to families living on air force 
navy army and marine corps bases child development centers 
provided in governmentbuilt and subsidized facilities by trained 
care givers and family day care homes usually provided in 
government housing by nonmilitary spouses 
the survey of 200 military installations in the continental 
united states found that child development centers have the 
capacity to care for more than 38500 children while 4557 day 
care homes can care for as many as 23417 children eighty percent 
of the remaining 24729 children who are on waiting lists need 
fullday care 
the survey by the congressional watchdog agency had no 
information on nationwide spending for military child care 
worldwide however operating costs for child care centers totaled 
1016 million in fiscal 1985 including 314 million in federally 
appropriated funds the report said by fiscal 1987 federal 
spending had increased 39 percent to 436 million out of a total 
cost of 1343 million the survey said 
if the program is to continue to grow many child care centers 
need to be renovated or built the gao said 
military parents child care needs are complicated by the fact 
that they often work unusual hours cant rely on extended family 
for help and because of frequent moves dont have the support of 
an established neighborhood according to the report 
