<TEXT>
a battle between industry giants over 
superabsorbent diapers and the millions of dollars that come 
through their sale has opened in us district court here 
in the case procter amp gamble co charges that the design of its 
highly successful superabsorbent pampers was copied by 
kimberlyclark corp in developing superabsorbent huggies 
the huge consumer products company wants us district judge 
falcon hawkins to order kimberlyclark to stop manufacturing the 
huggies and remove them from store shelves the company also is 
seeking unspecified monetary damages 
the stakes are high for making disposable diapers is a 33 
billionayear business according to court records 
procter amp gamble based in cincinnati is the industry leader 
with 47 percent of the market dallasbased kimberlyclark is no 2 
with about 30 percent industry analysts say 
as the trial got under way monday attorneys crowded the 
courtroom while scattered along the jury box were boxes and bags of 
diapers the case is expected to last at least three weeks 
allen gerstein representing procter amp gamble said pampg came up 
with the idea that made super absorbent diapers possible and took 
out a patent on the development 
the breakthrough he said allowed the manufacture of diapers 
that are generally thinner but more absorbent than regular more 
bulky disposables 
we stayed within the system while kimberlyclark disregarded 
and took unfair advantage of the system he told hawkins in his 
opening argument 
pampg researcher paul weisman developed a means for combining wood 
pulp fluff and super absorbent materials in the diaper to allow it 
to be made thinner gerstein said 
gerstein said kimberlyclark copied the idea shortly after the 
pampers were test marketed in wichita kan in 1984 
the introduction of the new diapers turned the diaper world on 
its ear he said 
but attorney h blair white representing kimberlyclark said 
this case is about two fiercely competitive companies each trying 
to improve baby diapers 
he charged that pampg never had a valid patent because it withheld 
important test information from the us patent office 
in addition he said the system weisman developed was already 
covered in a british patent for superabsorbing materials issued to 
an italian inventor in 1979 
in order to have a valid patent you cant be the second 
person or the 10th person to invent something you have to be the 
first he said 
white argued that kimberlyclark had widespread experience with 
superabsorbent materials as early as 1977 in the manufacture of 
tampons and adult diapers 
kimberlyclark didnt need lessons from anyone about super 
absorbent products white said noting that the only things our 
scientists learned from the wichita diapers was how not to make a 
diaper 
white said the problem with the pampers when they were 
introduced was that the superabsorbing material would come off on 
the skin of babies 
it was a problem kimberlyclark was trying to address in its own 
labs at the time he said adding the company eventually developed 
a system of putting the material farther away from the babies skin 
a system for which the company has been awarded a patent 
the case is being heard in a nonjury proceeding it was brought 
in south carolina because kimberlyclark runs a diaper 
manufacturing plant in beech island near aiken 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890411-0199 </DOCNO>
