<TEXT>
white house and congressional budget writers 
with deadlines slipping away pushed today to finish their talks on 
a compromise spending and tax package for next year 
were hoping to come to an agreement but we havent made it 
said rep bill frenzel of minnesota the senior republican on the 
house budget committee as he entered todays meeting 
when we get one issue resolved we run into another said 
sen pete v domenici rnm frenzels senate counterpart who 
said he was still optimistic 
the bargainers have been meeting behind closed doors for more 
than a month in search of a compromise plan for reducing the 
federal deficit to 100 billion next year as required by the 
grammrudman law 
several of the groups own informal deadlines for actions have 
passed with some more significant ones looming including 
congress april 15 deadline for passing a budget resolution the 
negotiators were pressing to finish today 
a budget pact would be formally announced at a white house 
meeting but without agreement today that was unlikely until next 
week because president bush is leaving town 
based on latest estimates and bushs 116 trillion spending 
plan about 28 billion in deficit reduction is required the group 
has agreed that about half would come from spending restraints and 
half from raising revenues 
the revenues include roughly 34 billion from selling 
government assets 52 billion from raising various fees for 
government services and some 56 billion would be in unspecified 
new taxes but presumably none that president bush would concede 
violate his campaign promise for no new taxes 
more than 7 billion in savings would be made by restraining 
entitlement programs those requiring direct benefit payments to 
individuals including more than 25 billion trimmed from the 
expected growth in medicare costs 
mondays session was dedicated to deciding generally where cuts 
in nonentitlement government programs would be made at the 
pentagon and at domestic agencies according to participants who 
spoke on the condition of anonymity 
bush proposed that military spending be allowed to grow with 
inflation while domestic programs other than his own initiatives 
would be frozen at the previous years levels democrats in the 
talks have proposed trimming back defense growth so that more 
domestic demands can be met 
the bargainers traded offers monday toward a possible compromise 
on those and on the small but also politically sensitive foreign 
aid budget 
bush has personally contacted at least one lawmaker to lobby 
against cuts in foreign aid a program now administered by his old 
friend secretary of state james baker who appeared before the 
negotiators early in the talks 
congress has a selfimposed april 15 deadline for producing a 
budget resolution and even if agreement is reached quickly that 
deadline will be missed by weeks 
even if the negotiators complete their task this week the house 
and senate budget committees must draft more detailed spending 
plans for each chamber to consider then the two chambers would 
need to approve a single compromise plan 
the budget which does not require the presidents signature 
serves as the guide for annual spending bills and tax legislation 
for the new fiscal year which begins oct 1 
if congress and the president dont by then bring down the 
deficit to within 10 billion of the 100 billion goal the 
administration is required under the grammrudman law to order 
acrosstheboard spending cuts to make up the difference 
