the international coffee organization cut its 
global export quota by 351000 bags tuesday to shore up falling 
prices 
the cut in the october 1988september 1989 quota was triggered 
automatically by a fall in the average coffee price below 115 a 
pound one bag equals 132 pounds 
the coffee organizations 15day composite indicator for monday 
calculated on tuesday dropped to 11498 from 11523 on friday 
the organization made up of coffee producer and consumer 
nations has set a target price for coffee of 120140 
in february it twice cut the global export quota when the 
average price fell below 120 a pound 
the three cuts affect only the quotas of countries producing the 
poorer grade robusta beans principally the ivory coast uganda and 
indonesia the organization wants to boost supplies of the prized 
arabica beans grown throughout latin america 
only if the price of arabica falls from its current level of 
140 a pound to under 130 will arabica producers face a 
reduction in their export quotas 
the robusta producers affected by tuesdays cut with the size 
of the reduction in parentheses are cameroon 38500 bags 
indonesia 78000 ivory coast 101500 madagascar 20000 
philippines 13000 uganda 67000 and zaire 33000 
