<TEXT>
northrop corp and five current and former 
employees were indicted tuesday on charges they conspired to 
defraud the government in building components for the guidance 
system for the cruise missile and the harrier jet fighter 
the 167count indictment announced by us attorney robert 
bonner charged that northrop and the five conspired to install 
install parts of the cruise missile system which failed to meet 
government specifications 
the indictment also alleged that lengthy reliability testing on 
the cruise missiles flight data transmitter was not performed as 
required and that three of the defendants supervised false testing 
and falsification of test results 
if convicted on all charges northrop faces a maximum fine of 
more than 30 million each of the individual defendants would face 
maximum jail sentences of five years on each count and fines 
ranging from 5000 to 250000 
todays indictment is part of our continuing efforts to 
identify prosecute and hopefully deter defense procurement 
fraud bonner said in a statement 
he said the indictment was the result of a twoyear probe by a 
multiagency task force 
there was no immediate reaction to the indictment from northrop 
obviously we havent seen it so we cant comment said greg 
waskul a spokesman at the century city office 
named in the indictment were joseph yamron a resident of 
massachusetts and vice president and general manager of the 
precision products divsion of northrop also named were leopold 
engler of massachusetts formerly a vice president with northrop 
charles gonsalves of glendora calif former manager of the 
western services department of northrop cheryl hannan of 
glendora formerly quality assurance supervisor for western 
services and howard hyde of yorba linda calif former chief 
engineer for western services 
with regard to the harrier jet project the indictment accused 
northrop gonzalves hyde and ms hannan of conspiring to defraud 
the government about the stabilization systems sold by northrop to 
be installed in the navy jet 
the indictment accused the defendants of failing to conduct 
vibration tests at levels required by the contract on sensor 
assemblies used in the jet and then falsely certifying they had 
been properly tested 
the harrier can take off from short fields and can hover and 
sophisticated stability controls are critical to its performance 
and safety 
on the cruise missile project the indictment charges that 
northrop yamron and engler knew that the flight data transmitter 
was required to withstand temperatures as low as 65 degrees but 
supplied parts that froze at temperatures of 40 to 50 degrees 
many of the cruise missiles presumed targets are deep within 
the soviet union where temperatures can drop to extreme levels 
should the flight data transmitter fail in extreme cold the weapon 
could not reach its target 
northrop produced and shipped approximately 1175 flight data 
transmitters between 1981 and 1989 for use in the missile which 
have been deployed on b52 and b1b bombers 
the company produced and shipped 189 sensor assemblies for the 
harrier jet between 1982 and 1989 
bonner said the air force and navy are now evaluating the 
evidence on the alleged falsifications in order to determine if 
action must be taken to ensure the reliability of the missiles and 
the harrier 
northrop also is the target of five civil lawsuits by former 
employees who alleged the company falsified test results and 
cheated the air force on the mx missile project 
in addition to wellpublicized battles with critics of the mx 
program the company faces a congressional investigation of 
allegations of improper payments to south korean businessmen in an 
unsuccessful effort to sell its f20 tigershark fighter in that 
country in 1984 
northrop is also the main contractor for the b2 stealth bomber 
</TEXT>
